<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910905-0013</DOCNO><DOCID>910905-0013.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Banca Nazionale del Lavoro:   Holders Give Bank Approval   To Revamp, Boost Capital</HL><DATE>09/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   I.BNL</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)</IN><RE>EUROPE (EU)ITALY (ITA)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Italy's state-owned Banca Nazionale del Lavoro, which hasbeen troubled by a loans-to-Iraq scandal and the collapse ofan Italian farm cooperative, won formal approval from itsowners to change its structure to a joint stock company.   The move is intended to improve BNL's management of itsown business, make internal divisions more accountable to topexecutives and improve its competitiveness.</LP><TEXT>   The Milan bank will increase its capital to 1.603 trillionlire from 1.579 trillion ($1.2 billion) and incorporating itsfour special credit institutes operating in the areas offilm, theater, tourism and industry into BNL's new parent,BNL Holding S.p.A.   The bank will remain state-controlled, with the TreasuryMinistry owning a direct 59% stake and the rest of the stockheld mainly by large state pension and insuranceinstitutions. However it will formally have the status of ashare-listing company, or Societa per Azioni -- thus theinitials S.p.A. -- clearing the way for a possible flotationof a minority of its stock on the Milan stock market in thefuture.   The restructuring, which will bring the bank capital gainstotaling 2.4 trillion lire, has been made possible by a 1989bank reform law.</TEXT></DOC>